Whether there are other routes to nepv besides respiratory transmission has been a hot issue for researchers.

On February 26, Professor Ye Shen, Deputy Dean of the First Affiliated College of Medicine of Zhejiang University and head of Ophthalmology, published an online study in the Journal of Medical Virology, this revealed the presence of a tear and conjunctival secretion sample from a patient with conjunctivitis in the study's new coronavirus patient sample, which tested positive for the virus in a nucleic acid test.

The study was led by Xia Jianhua and co-authored by Shen ye and Guo Dongyu. The first unit is the First Affiliated Hospital of Medical College of Zhejiang University.

Shen Ye said that the study of different modes of transmission is of great significance in understanding the law of transmission of new coronavirus, improving treatment methods and prevention and control measures.

Researchers from Zhejiang University studied a mixture of tear and conjunctival secretions from 30 patients with new coronary pneumonia diagnosed from January 26 to February 9 at the First Affiliated Hospital of Zhejiang University School of Medicine. In the Phase I study of 6 samples, no nucleic acid test was found positive for the virus. The team decided that the existing samples were not representative and comprehensive, and therefore needed to extend the observation cycle and remain in the isolation ward for sampling and research.

The team found conjunctivitis in the left eye of a patient with new coronary pneumonia, a red eye disease caused by the new crown, but not in the right eye. As previously understood, the patient had no conjunctivitis prior to admission. The other patients in this study tested negative for nucleic acid.

"The eye differences in this patient are very representative, and with our consent, we looked at whether conjunctivitis is associated with the virus. " Researchers at Zhejiang University found that the left eye with conjunctivitis was positive for the new coronavirus, while the right eye was negative. To ensure the accuracy of the study, three nucleic acid tests were performed on conjunctival secretions in both eyes, and the results were consistent.

At present, the patient through anti-virus comprehensive treatment, the overall cure of the case, conjunctivitis also improved, once again to detect the eye virus negative. How the patient developed conjunctival inflammation from the new coronavirus is still under investigation, the researchers said.

According to Shen, this study led to the following conclusions: 1. Left eye conjunctivitis is associated with the new coronavirus; 2. There is a risk of ocular transmission of the new coronavirus; 3. Respiratory tract may not be the only route of transmission of the new coronavirus.

Shen said the study's practical significance is to prompt medical workers to wear goggles as well as face masks when examining suspicious cases. This study provides scientific basis for further improvement of national guidelines and standards for the prevention and control of new coronavirus.

"The conjunctiva is what we usually call the outermost layer of the whites of the eyes. It is a barrier between the eye and the air. Oxygen can be absorbed in the conjunctiva and participate in metabolism. Its normal function can block the invasion of pathogens such as bacteria and viruses, " Shen said, whether the new coronavirus can find the human body immune loophole to enter the human body remains to be further studied, looking forward to solve the mystery through cooperation.

The research was supported by the major science and technology project of Zhejiang Science and Technology Department.
